rsQLoRA: Fine-tune Llama 3 with Higher Ranks and QLoRA

Evaluating the impact of rank-stabilized LoRA on recent LLMs and when using QLoRA

With parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods such as LoRA, we can fine-tune LLMs on consumer hardware. For instance, with LoRA, it is possible to fine-tune Llama 3 8B using a 16 GB GPU.

Fine-tune Llama 3 on Your Computer

Apr 22
Read full story

However, LoRA is only approximating full fine-tuning. Previous work has shown that the capacity of a LoRA adapter to learn is limited by the low-rank nature of the update applied to the adapters parameters during fine-tuning.

Increasing the rank, which is a hyperparameter of LoRA, sounds like an intuitive solution to increase the rank of the update and potentially improve fine-tuning. In practice, increasing the rank is often ineffective. Various methods have been proposed to leverage higher LoRA ranks. One such method is Rank-stabilized LoRA (rsLoRA), which is straightforward enough to be supported by many fine-tuning frameworks.

In this article, I explain rsLoRA and apply it to Llama 3. We will verify whether rsLoRA has a positive impact when fine-tuning high-rank adapters for Llama 3.

Ive also implemented a notebook showing how to use rsLoRA, in combination with QLoRA, here:

Get the notebook (#84)

rsLoRA: LoRA but with an Additional Square-root

rsLoRA is presented in this paper:

A Rank Stabilization Scaling Factor for Fine-Tuning with LoRA

The main motivation behind this work is that LoRA fine-tuning with higher ranks, e.g., when the rank is greater than 100, is often ineffective. Due to this lack of effectiveness of higher ranks, it is common to choose a low rank by default for LoRA fine-tuning and not try higher ranks, assuming that it wont yield better results.

Standard LoRA includes a scaling factor that balances the weight of the adapter. It is computed with the rank r and hyperparameter as follows:

r

The rsLoRA paper demonstrates that for sufficiently higher ranks r, the learning will collapse or will be unstable. This is intuitive. For a higher r, the impact of the adapter over the base model will decrease. In other words, while increasing r augments the number of trainable parameters, it also reduces the influence of these parameters over the base model on top of which the adapter is fine-tuned.

In my notebooks and tutorials, I usually set r=. If I set the rank to 16, the alpha is also set to 16. If I set the rank to 1024, the alpha is also set to 1024. This way, the scaling factor is always 1, and increasing r doesnt reduce the impact of the adapter. This is naive but it works well for low ranks.

rsLoRA is a better alternative that simply applies a square root to r to give more influence to the adapter for higher ranks:

r

If we set r=, for r=1024, the scaling factor will be 1024/32=32, i.e., the adapter will be 32 times stronger with rsLoRA than with standard LoRA.

The author of rsLoRA empirically verified that it improves fine-tuning with various values for r.

As we can see, for higher ranks, such as 1,024 and 2,048, standard LoRA is not working well and achieves a higher training loss while rsLoRA consistently improves the training loss as the rank gets higher.

If you are doing LoRA fine-tuning and if you have more GPU memory available, increasing the rank of the LoRA adapters with rsLoRA should yield better results.

Does it still work with recent LLMs, such as Llama 3, and when the model is quantized, i.e., using QLoRA?

Lets see.

Share

rsQLoRA for Llama 3

There are two ways to use rsLoRA:

  1. Take the same alpha that you would usually use with LoRA and multiply it by the square root of the rank:

rsLoRA=LoRAr

If you used to set LoRAs alpha to 16 and choose a rank of 16, your new alpha for rsLoRA should be:

rsLoRA=1616=164=64

  1. Set rslora=True in the LoraConfig of Hugging Face PEFT. This is also supported by Unsloth.

The first method would work with all the frameworks already supporting LoRA. The second one just spares you some calculations.

With Hugging Face PEFT, it can be done as follows:

Standard LoRA
peft_config = LoraConfig(
        lora_alpha=1024,
        lora_dropout=0.05,
        r=1024,
        bias="none",
        task_type="CAUSAL_LM",
        target_modules= ['k_proj', 'q_proj', 'v_proj', 'o_proj', "gate_proj", "down_proj", "up_proj"]
)
rsLoRA: Method 1
peft_config = LoraConfig(
        lora_alpha=32768,
        lora_dropout=0.05,
        r=1024,
        bias="none",
        task_type="CAUSAL_LM",
        target_modules= ['k_proj', 'q_proj', 'v_proj', 'o_proj', "gate_proj", "down_proj", "up_proj"]
)
rsLoRA: Method 2
peft_config = LoraConfig(
        lora_alpha=1024,
        lora_dropout=0.05,
        r=1024,
        use_rslora=True,
        bias="none",
        task_type="CAUSAL_LM",
        target_modules= ['k_proj', 'q_proj', 'v_proj', 'o_proj', "gate_proj", "down_proj", "up_proj"]
)

Note: As it clearly appears with Method 1, using a rank of 1,024 means that the real alpha used when applying rsLoRA is extremely high, at 32,768.

For rsQLoRA, the only difference is that we quantize the base LLM as we would for a standard QLoRA fine-tuning.

You can find the fine-tuning code in the notebook (link in the introduction).

Does rsLoRA work with Llama 3?

I couldnt get good results. And I tried many hyperparameter configurations:

  • with/without rslora=True,

  • with lower ranks

  • with lower alpha

rsLoRA is supposed to work better for high rank. However, for instance, using this configuration:

peft_config = LoraConfig(
        lora_alpha=1024,
        lora_dropout=0.05,
        r=1024,
        use_rslora=True,
        bias="none",
        task_type="CAUSAL_LM",
        target_modules= ['k_proj', 'q_proj', 'v_proj', 'o_proj', "gate_proj", "down_proj", "up_proj"]
)

The training loss is near 10 and remains high while without rsLoRA, but using the same rank and alpha, LoRA has almost a normal training loss below 2.

Here are the learning curves for all the interesting configurations that I have tried:

Note: All the configurations I tried are with Llama 3 8B quantized to 4-bit with bitsandbytes. I aggressively zoomed in on the learning curves to be able to see most of them.

Main observations:

  • Standard LoRA with r=128 and alpha=128 works the best (black curve). This configuration is equivalent to rsLoRA with r=128 and alpha =12. As we can see, the learning curves are almost identical.

  • Decreasing the alpha when using rsLoRA helps.

  • The learning curve for rsLoRA with r=256 and alpha =256 was so bad that most of it is not on the plot.

  • None of these configurations achieve a loss as low as the one we can achieve with r=16, as shown in this article:

rsLoRA does not work? Why?

It doesnt work for this specific setting but I could see many experiment reports showing better learning curves with rsLoRA. However, I couldnt find many reports on rsLoRA applied to Llama 3 and with QLoRA.

Decreasing the learning rate would definitely help to reduce the loss but the rsLoRA paper clearly mentions that rsLoRA alone, without modifying the learning rate, should work.

So why rsLoRA doesnt work here? I can only assume that this particular training data doesnt benefit from a higher LoRA rank. It is a rather small dataset. Further experiments would be need to investigate the potential of rsLoRA with Llama 3 quantized to 4-bit.

Conclusion

Rank-stabilized LoRA is an interesting and simple idea to better exploit LoRA with higher ranks. However, as we saw in this article, it doesnt always work.

I recommend treating it as an additional hyperparameter. If you have enough memory to increase the LoRA rank, increase it without rsLoRA. If you getter a better loss than with lower ranks, it might be a sign that rsLoRA would work better.
